		Suppose a vector \uvec{v} could have two negatives, (-\uvec{v})_1 and (-\uvec{v})_2. But then,


				(-\uvec{v})_2
				\amp= (-\uvec{v})_2 + \zerovec \amp
				\amp\text{(i)}

				\amp= (-\uvec{v})_2 + \bbrac{\uvec{v} + (-\uvec{v})_1} \amp
				\amp\text{(ii)}

				\amp= \bbrac{(-\uvec{v})_2 + \uvec{v}} + (-\uvec{v})_1 \amp
				\amp\text{(iii)}

				\amp= \bbrac{\uvec{v} + (-\uvec{v})_2} + (-\uvec{v})_1 \amp
				\amp\text{(iv)}

				\amp= \zerovec + (-\uvec{v})_1 \amp
				\amp\text{(v)}

				\amp= (-\uvec{v})_1 + \zerovec \amp
				\amp\text{(vi)}

				\amp= (-\uvec{v})_1 \amp
				\amp\text{(vii)},


		with justifications


